				<div id="post-549" class="post-549 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-guessing-geodesics category-hyperbolicity-of-complexes">
											<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="https://alexsisto.wordpress.com/2013/02/08/hyperbolicity-of-the-curve-graph-the-proof-from-the-book/" rel="bookmark">Hyperbolicity of the curve graph: the proof from The&nbsp;Book</a></h2>					
					<div class="entry-meta">
						<span class="meta-prep meta-prep-author">Posted on</span> <a href="https://alexsisto.wordpress.com/2013/02/08/hyperbolicity-of-the-curve-graph-the-proof-from-the-book/" title="10:11 pm" rel="bookmark"><span class="entry-date">February 8, 2013</span></a>						<span class="by-author"><span class="sep">by</span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://alexsisto.wordpress.com/author/alexsisto/" title="View all posts by Alex Sisto" rel="author">Alex Sisto</a></span> </span>					</div><!-- .entry-meta -->

					<div class="entry-content">
						<p>In this post I’ll talk about a lovely <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1301.5577" target="_blank">paper</a> by Sebastian Hensel, Piotr Przytycki and Richard Webb. They show that all curve graphs are 17-hyperbolic. Hyperbolicity of curve graphs is a very very very useful* property because mapping class groups act nicely on them, so you can prove all sorts of things using this action.<br>
The proofs available before HPW were quite complicated and relied on Teichmüller theory, so I was quite amazed to see that this could be proven in 6 self-contained pages. And, as the authors pointed out to me: “Well, there’s one page of introduction and one page of references.”</p>
<p>This post is an illustrated guide to the proof. I won’t define arc/curve complexes here, but I plan to write a BI soon. The more loudly you complain, the sooner I will actually do.</p>
<p>Ok, let’s start. First of all, as it turns out it’s more convenient to deal with arc graphs instead of curve graphs.</p>
<p><strong>Reduction to the arc graph.</strong> (Really, just skip this <img draggable="false" class="emoji" alt="😀" src="https://s0.wp.com/wp-content/mu-plugins/wpcom-smileys/twemoji/2/svg/1f600.svg"> ) Here’s a very quick sketch of how to deduce hyperbolicity of curve graphs once we know it for arc graphs, which for the moment we assume we do.<br>
If we are dealing with a (complicated) surface with boundary then the idea we can use is that one can construct a path in the curve complex starting from a path <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cgamma&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\gamma" title="\gamma" class="latex"> in the arc complex by considering curves disjoint from the arcs appearing along <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cgamma&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\gamma" title="\gamma" class="latex"> (it will be clearer later how to exploit this, if you don’t know how to do it already). I’ll be honest, just this one time: There is a subtle issue I’m sweeping under the carpet here, but I would like not to make the post too technical…<br>
Anyway, suppose instead that your surface, <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=S&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="S" title="S" class="latex">, is closed. If you call <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=S%27&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="S'" title="S'" class="latex"> the surface obtained by adding a boundary component, then you have a boundary-forgetting map. This map is Lipschitz, this is immediate, and has a section, constructed as follows. Choose a hyperbolic metric on <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=S&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="S" title="S" class="latex"> and realise all (homotopy classes of) curves as geodesics. Now you can take a puncture outside the union of all such (countably many) geodesics.&nbsp;Using the two properties it’s not hard to see that the curve graph of <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=S&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="S" title="S" class="latex"> must be hyperbolic as well. The details are in section 5 of the paper.</p>
<p><strong>Unicorns!</strong> Ok, let’s now take an arc graph. The strategy to show it’s hyperbolic is to prove that, as David puts it, “it smells hyperbolic”**, i.e. that there exists a family of preferred paths with nice properties (you may wish to take a look at <a href="https://alexsisto.wordpress.com/2012/07/16/bi-guessing-geodesics-in-hyperbolic-spaces/" target="_blank">this pos</a>t <img draggable="false" class="emoji" alt="🙂" src="https://s0.wp.com/wp-content/mu-plugins/wpcom-smileys/twemoji/2/svg/1f642.svg"> ). The most important property that this family should satisfy is that triangles of preferred paths should be slim. The other properties you need (in simplified form) are that a preferred path is a geodesic if the endpoints have distance at most 1 and that a subpath of a preferred path is a preferred path.<br>
HPW called the nice paths they constructed unicorn paths (!). They were initially called one-corner paths, but then Piotr realised that one-corner and unicorn are almost the same word in Polish, and that unicorn would be a much more awesome name.<br>
And now, here are the paths. You have to start with two arcs in minimal position, <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex"> and <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=b&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="b" title="b" class="latex">, and it’s convenient to fix preferred endpoints, <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Calpha&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\alpha" title="\alpha" class="latex"> and <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cbeta&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\beta" title="\beta" class="latex">. We can assume that <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a%2Cb&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a,b" title="a,b" class="latex"> intersect minimally. The arcs appearing along the path from <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex"> to <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=b&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="b" title="b" class="latex">, the unicorn arcs, have a rather simple form: You travel along <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex"> until you reach some intersection point, <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cpi&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\pi" title="\pi" class="latex">, and then you go to <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cbeta&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\beta" title="\beta" class="latex">.</p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicorn1.png"><img data-attachment-id="569" data-permalink="https://alexsisto.wordpress.com/2013/02/08/hyperbolicity-of-the-curve-graph-the-proof-from-the-book/unicorn-2/" data-orig-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicorn1.png?w=512&amp;h=288" data-orig-size="1311,738" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;}" data-image-title="unicorn" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicorn1.png?w=512&amp;h=288?w=300" data-large-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicorn1.png?w=512&amp;h=288?w=640" class="aligncenter  wp-image-569" alt="unicorn" src="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicorn1.png?w=512&amp;h=288" width="512" height="288" srcset="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicorn1.png?w=512&amp;h=288 512w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicorn1.png?w=1024&amp;h=576 1024w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicorn1.png?w=150&amp;h=84 150w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicorn1.png?w=300&amp;h=169 300w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicorn1.png?w=768&amp;h=432 768w" sizes="(max-width: 512px) 100vw, 512px"></a></p>
<p>Not all intersection points work, because the procedure described above might not give an embedded arc (look at <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Ctau&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\tau" title="\tau" class="latex">, for example).<br>
Let us also include <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex"> and <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=b&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="b" title="b" class="latex"> in the collection of unicorn arcs. So, given <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a%2Cb&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a,b" title="a,b" class="latex"> you have finitely many arcs, and there is a natural order on them: You write <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c%3Cc%27&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c&lt;c'" title="c&lt;c'" class="latex"> if the common subpath of <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c" title="c" class="latex"> and <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex"> is longer than the common subpath of <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c%27&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c'" title="c'" class="latex"> and <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex">. The idea is that you are describing a path from <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex"> to <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=b&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="b" title="b" class="latex">, so the paths more closely resembling <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex"> should appear first.<br>
Now, we have to check that we actually described a path, i.e. that if <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c%27&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c'" title="c'" class="latex"> is the successor of <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c" title="c" class="latex"> then <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c%2Cc%27&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c,c'" title="c,c'" class="latex"> can be realised disjointly.<br>
The recipe to construct the successor is simple. Let <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cpi&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\pi" title="\pi" class="latex"> be the intersection point defining <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c" title="c" class="latex">, and let <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=b%27&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="b'" title="b'" class="latex"> be the subpath of <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c" title="c" class="latex"> from <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cpi&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\pi" title="\pi" class="latex"> to <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cbeta&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\beta" title="\beta" class="latex">. Just travel along <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex"> after <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cpi&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\pi" title="\pi" class="latex"> until you hit <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=b%27&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="b'" title="b'" class="latex"> in some point <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cpi%27&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\pi'" title="\pi'" class="latex">. Then it’s not hard to convince yourself that <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cpi%27&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\pi'" title="\pi'" class="latex"> defines <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c%27&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c'" title="c'" class="latex">.</p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornsucc.png"><img data-attachment-id="551" data-permalink="https://alexsisto.wordpress.com/2013/02/08/hyperbolicity-of-the-curve-graph-the-proof-from-the-book/unicornsucc/" data-orig-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornsucc.png?w=576&amp;h=328" data-orig-size="1312,747" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;}" data-image-title="unicornsucc" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornsucc.png?w=576&amp;h=328?w=300" data-large-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornsucc.png?w=576&amp;h=328?w=640" class="aligncenter  wp-image-551" alt="unicornsucc" src="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornsucc.png?w=576&amp;h=328" width="576" height="328" srcset="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornsucc.png?w=576&amp;h=328 576w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornsucc.png?w=1152&amp;h=656 1152w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornsucc.png?w=150&amp;h=85 150w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornsucc.png?w=300&amp;h=171 300w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornsucc.png?w=768&amp;h=437 768w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornsucc.png?w=1024&amp;h=583 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 576px) 100vw, 576px"></a></p>
<p>The picture also illustrates how to realise <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c%2Cc%27&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c,c'" title="c,c'" class="latex"> disjointly.</p>
<p><strong>Slim unicorns!</strong> And here is the cool part. Unicorn triangles are 1-slim, i.e. given <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a%2Cb%2Cd&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a,b,d" title="a,b,d" class="latex"> and a unicorn arc <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c" title="c" class="latex">, defined by <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cpi%5Cin+a%5Ccap+b&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\pi\in a\cap b" title="\pi\in a\cap b" class="latex">, on the unicorn path <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=P%28a%2Cb%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="P(a,b)" title="P(a,b)" class="latex"> from <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex"> to <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=b&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="b" title="b" class="latex"> there is a point on <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=P%28a%2Cd%29%5Ccup+P%28b%2Cd%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="P(a,d)\cup P(b,d)" title="P(a,d)\cup P(b,d)" class="latex"> at distance at most 1 from <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c" title="c" class="latex">. The proof is very easy, just travel along <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=d&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="d" title="d" class="latex"> until you hit <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c" title="c" class="latex">, then go to <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Calpha&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\alpha" title="\alpha" class="latex"> or <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cbeta&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\beta" title="\beta" class="latex">, whichever you can reach avoiding <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cpi&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\pi" title="\pi" class="latex">.</p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornslim1.png"><img data-attachment-id="590" data-permalink="https://alexsisto.wordpress.com/2013/02/08/hyperbolicity-of-the-curve-graph-the-proof-from-the-book/unicornslim-2/" data-orig-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornslim1.png?w=512&amp;h=262" data-orig-size="1166,597" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;}" data-image-title="unicornslim" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornslim1.png?w=512&amp;h=262?w=300" data-large-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornslim1.png?w=512&amp;h=262?w=640" class="aligncenter  wp-image-590" alt="unicornslim" src="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornslim1.png?w=512&amp;h=262" width="512" height="262" srcset="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornslim1.png?w=512&amp;h=262 512w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornslim1.png?w=1024&amp;h=524 1024w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornslim1.png?w=150&amp;h=77 150w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornslim1.png?w=300&amp;h=154 300w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornslim1.png?w=768&amp;h=393 768w" sizes="(max-width: 512px) 100vw, 512px"></a></p>
<p>The picture hopefully clearly illustrates that the unicorn arc <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c%27&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c'" title="c'" class="latex"> we just constructed can be realised disjointly from <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c" title="c" class="latex">.<br>
The authors told me that the initial argument for 1-slimness of triangles&nbsp;was based on their dismantlability, you may wish to take a look at this&nbsp;<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1205.0513" target="_blank">paper</a>.</p>
<p><strong>The technical bit.</strong> You need one more property to show that arc graphs are hyperbolic and unicorn paths are close to geodesics, that is to say that a subpath of a unicorn path is a unicorn path. Well, this is not actually true, sometimes you can have a subpath of a unicorn path of length 2 connecting points at distance 1 in the arc graph. But that’s the only bad thing that can happen, and this is good enough for us.<br>
Stare at the recipe I told you about earlier to construct the successor. Done? It might now seem to you that if you have two unicorn arcs <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c_1%2Cc_2&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c_1,c_2" title="c_1,c_2" class="latex"> constructed from <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a%2Cb&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a,b" title="a,b" class="latex">, the recipe will give you exactly the same successor of <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c_1&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c_1" title="c_1" class="latex"> regardless of whether you work “between <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex"> and <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=b&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="b" title="b" class="latex">” or “between <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c_1&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c_1" title="c_1" class="latex"> and <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c_2&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c_2" title="c_2" class="latex">.” So… what’s the problem? The problem is that <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c_1%2Cc_2&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c_1,c_2" title="c_1,c_2" class="latex"> might not be in minimal position! <img draggable="false" class="emoji" alt="😦" src="https://s0.wp.com/wp-content/mu-plugins/wpcom-smileys/twemoji/2/svg/1f626.svg"><br>
So you have to understand when they don’t intersect minimally (Sublemma 3.6 in the paper). You can reduce to the case <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a%3Dc_1&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a=c_1" title="a=c_1" class="latex"> and <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c_2&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c_2" title="c_2" class="latex"> the predecessor of <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=b&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="b" title="b" class="latex">, once again because of the recipe for the successor. The predecessor of <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=b&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="b" title="b" class="latex"> is the unicorn arc travelling as little as possible along <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex">, so you just have to find the first intersection point <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cpi&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\pi" title="\pi" class="latex"> of <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a%2Cb&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a,b" title="a,b" class="latex"> along <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex">.</p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon1.png"><img data-attachment-id="570" data-permalink="https://alexsisto.wordpress.com/2013/02/08/hyperbolicity-of-the-curve-graph-the-proof-from-the-book/unicornbigon-2/" data-orig-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon1.png?w=576&amp;h=293" data-orig-size="1291,659" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;}" data-image-title="unicornbigon" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon1.png?w=576&amp;h=293?w=300" data-large-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon1.png?w=576&amp;h=293?w=640" class="aligncenter  wp-image-570" alt="unicornbigon" src="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon1.png?w=576&amp;h=293" width="576" height="293" srcset="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon1.png?w=574&amp;h=293 574w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon1.png?w=1148&amp;h=586 1148w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon1.png?w=150&amp;h=77 150w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon1.png?w=300&amp;h=153 300w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon1.png?w=768&amp;h=392 768w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon1.png?w=1024&amp;h=523 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 576px) 100vw, 576px"></a></p>
<p>(Yes, there’s a reason why I’ve drawn the picture in that weird way, see below <img draggable="false" class="emoji" alt="😉" src="https://s0.wp.com/wp-content/mu-plugins/wpcom-smileys/twemoji/2/svg/1f609.svg"> )<br>
Let me recall that two arcs are in minimal position if there are no bigons or half bigons:</p>
<p><a href="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal1.png"><img data-attachment-id="554" data-permalink="https://alexsisto.wordpress.com/2013/02/08/hyperbolicity-of-the-curve-graph-the-proof-from-the-book/minimal1/" data-orig-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal1.png?w=640&amp;h=116" data-orig-size="1059,193" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;}" data-image-title="minimal1" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal1.png?w=640&amp;h=116?w=300" data-large-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal1.png?w=640&amp;h=116?w=640" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-554" alt="minimal1" src="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal1.png?w=640&amp;h=116" width="640" height="116" srcset="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal1.png?w=636&amp;h=116 636w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal1.png?w=150&amp;h=27 150w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal1.png?w=300&amp;h=55 300w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal1.png?w=768&amp;h=140 768w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal1.png?w=1024&amp;h=187 1024w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal1.png 1059w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px"></a></p>
<p>Now, there cannot be a bigon between <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex"> and <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=c_2&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="c_2" title="c_2" class="latex">, for otherwise you can easily convince yourself that there would be one between <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex"> and <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=b&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="b" title="b" class="latex">. Similarly, you can only have a half-bigon if <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cpi&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="\pi" title="\pi" class="latex"> appears on it:</p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal2.png"><img data-attachment-id="555" data-permalink="https://alexsisto.wordpress.com/2013/02/08/hyperbolicity-of-the-curve-graph-the-proof-from-the-book/minimal2/" data-orig-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal2.png?w=297&amp;h=154" data-orig-size="371,193" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;}" data-image-title="minimal2" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal2.png?w=297&amp;h=154?w=300" data-large-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal2.png?w=297&amp;h=154?w=371" class="aligncenter  wp-image-555" alt="minimal2" src="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal2.png?w=297&amp;h=154" width="297" height="154" srcset="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal2.png?w=297&amp;h=154 297w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal2.png?w=150&amp;h=78 150w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal2.png?w=300&amp;h=156 300w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/minimal2.png 371w" sizes="(max-width: 297px) 100vw, 297px"></a></p>
<p>So, if there is a half-bigon, then it must look like this:</p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon21.png"><img data-attachment-id="571" data-permalink="https://alexsisto.wordpress.com/2013/02/08/hyperbolicity-of-the-curve-graph-the-proof-from-the-book/unicornbigon2-2/" data-orig-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon21.png?w=576&amp;h=313" data-orig-size="1291,702" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;}" data-image-title="unicornbigon2" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon21.png?w=576&amp;h=313?w=300" data-large-file="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon21.png?w=576&amp;h=313?w=640" class="aligncenter  wp-image-571" alt="unicornbigon2" src="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon21.png?w=576&amp;h=313" width="576" height="313" srcset="https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon21.png?w=576&amp;h=313 576w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon21.png?w=1152&amp;h=626 1152w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon21.png?w=150&amp;h=82 150w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon21.png?w=300&amp;h=163 300w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon21.png?w=768&amp;h=418 768w, https://alexsisto.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/unicornbigon21.png?w=1024&amp;h=557 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 576px) 100vw, 576px"></a></p>
<p>So, you have a very good control on what can go wrong. I won’t go into details but I hope that you’ll find it reasonable to believe that it’s possible to deal with this problem.</p>
<p>And that’s the end <img draggable="false" class="emoji" alt="🙂" src="https://s0.wp.com/wp-content/mu-plugins/wpcom-smileys/twemoji/2/svg/1f642.svg"></p>
<p>Let me add the comment that Lemma 3.4, which I didn’t go into, is there just to get a better constant at the end, but without it you can prove, say, 19-hyperbolicity.<br>
The lemma says that given 3 unicorn paths forming a triangle you can find a triple of points on them at pairwise distance at most 1. If you allow yourself to substitute 1 with 3, this follows from what we already know. In fact, suppose you start at <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=a&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="a" title="a" class="latex"> and move towards <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=b&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="b" title="b" class="latex">. At first, you’ll be 1-close to <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=P%28a%2Cc%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="P(a,c)" title="P(a,c)" class="latex">, and at some point you’ll be 1-close to <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=P%28b%2Cc%29&amp;bg=ffffff&amp;fg=333333&amp;s=0" alt="P(b,c)" title="P(b,c)" class="latex">. When the switch happens, you have the 3 points you’re looking for. Btw, analysing this idea gives you a way of finding your candidate points at pairwise distance 1.</p>
<p>*David Hume was next to me when I wrote this and said “I have a paper that relies on that, so I’m not going to argue.”<br>
** David suggested I add “I would like to thank David for being so quotable.”</p>
